/*******************************************************************************
    The { and } modifiers skip to and skip over
*******************************************************************************/
    The delimitRecord rule uses skip overs, that is what the } modifier does.
    The result (whatever gets skipped up to the skip match) is put in the
    label the modifier is associated with. That is, the skip returns everything
    up to the skip stashed in the label.
        If the skip modifier is { the rule input is left pointing at the match.
        If the modifier is } rule input is left pointing just after the match.
        In both cases, the skip match is ignored.
    The value of the skip label can determine the skip match. To clarify,
    given the attribute: countField}=1 countField is the label, } is its
    modifier, and 1 is its value
        If the value is a set, the skip matches against the set.
        If it is a string its text is matched against.
        If it is numeric, it does not change the match but determines the
            value of the label after the match. That is, the label value
            will be either a count or a number (floating point).
        The default skip match (when the label value is not a set or a string)
        is a comma (useful for processing comma delimited files).
    Fields w/o a label (no label is set w/modifier -), as in skip-}=3,
    ignore fields skipped over, and the number of fields ignored is determined
    by the value of the label if it is numeric. Thus skip-}=3 ignores 3 fields.
    If you want to capture the skip match, use { and the following rule will
    match against it.
        That is, label{ nextRule=matchValue will return the match value in
        nextRule (actually, in the nextRule label).

    The delimitRecord rule applied to commaStuff, both defined above as
        delimitRecord isRule countField}=1 skip-}=3 numberField}=1.0 stringField};
        commaStuff="44,two,  forty three,six,6.7,ninety one";)
    uses the default comma skip match and sets countField to 44; ignores
    fields: two, forty three, and six; sets numberField to 6.7; and sets
    stringField to "ninety one".
    
/*******************************************************************************
    Rule expressions look like method invocations and apply a rule to its argument
*******************************************************************************/
    A rule expression like: rule(field) can be used as a command, a method call
    in an action, or as an attribute. It applies the rule to the contents
    of field (field is its argument and is expected to be a string).
    
    The basic idea with rule expressions is it allows you to apply a rule to selected
    input as opposed to applying a rule on the input stream, which is the norm for rules.
    
    Using a rule expression as an attribute is still WIP

